aws::graph::propositions: Robinson R22 Engine Characteristics
The Robinson R22 achieves acceptable high-altitude performance by derating the engine at sea level.
The Robinson R22 does not use supercharging for engine performance.
The Robinson R22 does not use turbocharging for engine performance.
Avoiding forced induction systems saves weight in the Robinson R22.
Avoiding forced induction systems saves cost in the Robinson R22.
Avoiding forced induction systems reduces complexity in the Robinson R22.
Avoiding forced induction systems prevents unreliability in the Robinson R22.
Avoiding forced induction systems prevents shortened engine life in the Robinson R22.
The Robinson R22 uses a carburetor to provide the air-fuel mixture.
Carbureted engines are susceptible to carburetor icing.
Carburetor icing is most likely to occur when there is a low 11 °C (20 °F) difference between the outside air temperature and dew point.
The difference between outside air temperature and dew point is called the "dew point spread".
Carburetor icing is most likely to occur when there are visible signs of moisture in the atmosphere.
Carburetor icing can lead to loss of engine power.
Carburetor icing can lead to total shutdown of the engine if not corrected.
The Robinson R22 has a carburetor heat control.
The carburetor heat control supplies heated air to the carburetor.
Heated air can prevent carburetor icing.
Heated air can cure carburetor icing.
Using carburetor heat causes a reduction in engine power output.
Engine power is reduced with carburetor heat because hot air is less dense.
Hot air enriches the fuel-air mixture.

text:
By derating the engine at sea level, the R22 achieves acceptable high-altitude performance without use of supercharging or turbocharging, thus saving the weight, cost, complexity, unreliability, and shortened engine life of a forced induction system.
A carburetor is used to provide the air-fuel mixture.  Carbureted engines are susceptible to carburetor icing, a condition most likely to occur in conditions of a low 11 °C (20 °F) difference  between the outside air temperature and dew point (the "dew point spread"), as well as visible signs of moisture in the atmosphere.  Icing can lead to loss of engine power, and if not corrected, total shutdown of the engine.  A carburetor heat control is used to supply heated air to the carburetor; this can prevent or cure icing, but also causes a reduction in engine power output because hot air is less dense, enriching the fuel-air mixture.
